To sum it up, I personally think that "The Four Seas" is a terrible movie in every sense of the word.
But if you say this movie has no highlights, that's not entirely true; at least the soundtrack was well-chosen.
There are many kinds of bad movies. One kind can make you fall asleep in the movie theater, and another kind can make you indignant after watching it. "The Four Seas" is like a monkey on Mount Emei to the audience. It can ignite your anger in countless ways.
Han Han is truly gifted at insulting the audience.
What's most painful about this film is that it feels like a creation from a Cleveland novel, indescribable and riddled with plot holes, much like the trench coat worn by Mark Gor.
Even after watching it, you might wonder if there are any hidden metaphors by the director, but after careful consideration, you'll find that it's actually just a pile of shit.
Let me first briefly explain some of the plot points that I find difficult to understand.
The male protagonist lives on a small island in the south, where he lives with his grandmother.
Her grandmother had a wish to see snow, so the plot arranged for an old man from the neighborhood to drive her to Northeast China to see the snow in a minivan.
An elderly person traveled from the south to the northeast in a minivan to see snow?
He and his father are quite reassured about this.
And then the old man disappeared without a trace.
How did the female lead's brother obtain a business license to run a hotel on an abandoned ship?
How could the motorcycle gang thugs on the island so easily close off a section of mountain road?
Then the truck delivering steel bars was parked in the middle of the road, and the truck driver couldn't be found anywhere.
The props look way too obvious.
Why would a petty hoodlum with a poor credit history and suspected criminal activity become an auxiliary police officer?
Why didn't they call the police when faced with loan sharks? In the movie, the police even specifically asked if they were in any trouble.
An adult knows how to use a smartphone but doesn't know how to open a hotel room door with a key card, and then forces the hotel owner to let the adult sleep outside the room all night because they can't find the hotel owner.
These inexplicable plot points permeate the entire film, and they are so absurd that recalling them still causes me pain.
Aside from the plot, what's worse is the film's theme, or rather, the film has no theme at all; it's just a hideous Frankenstein's monster.
At the beginning of the film, you might think he wanted to make a comedy. After about 20 minutes, you might guess it's an inspirational film. Halfway through, you might think it's a drama about the hardships of life for young people in small towns. After watching it, you have no idea what you actually watched. This leads to deep self-doubt: why did I go to the cinema to watch poop during the Chinese New Year?
Most people are already very familiar with the formulas of various movies. For example, if you want to make a movie about motorcyclists, you can combine inspirational stories with comedy and tell the audience how a talented rookie gradually achieves success.
If you want to make a romance film, then just tell the story of the love triangle between a small-town youth who loves riding motorcycles and a waitress.
If you want to reflect reality, then at the very least your plot cannot contain anything that contradicts the normal world.
(For example, the character played by Yin Zheng whose new motorcycle was burned but could still sing), so we can't come up with some outlandish ideas that even Kennedy couldn't stand.
As for the female lead, she's clearly not mentally challenged, but in some ways she acts like a 5-year-old child. I really don't know if it's due to her acting skills or the director's requirements.
There's another thing I don't quite understand: why is Han Han, as a race car driver, so keen on adding car crash scenes to his own movies?
Is the release of such a film during the Spring Festival simply meant to annoy or upset audiences?
