South African doctor: Omeprung is highly contagious but mostly causes mild symptoms.
Many doctors and medical experts in South Africa believe that the Omega variant of the coronavirus causes milder symptoms than the Delta variant, although it spreads faster.
According to the Associated Press, as the Omekkaron variant spreads in South Africa, a medical organization of more than 5,000 doctors in Gauteng province reported that the COVID-19 patients they are currently treating are experiencing mild symptoms, such as body aches and coughs, which are similar to those of the flu.
The organization's director, Dr. Unben Pillay, said he sees dozens of patients every day, but none of them have needed to be hospitalized yet.
Pillay said, "They were able to control the disease at home, and most people recovered within 10 to 14 days of isolation."
He said this includes elderly patients and those with pre-existing health conditions, who are already more likely to develop severe illness from coronavirus infection.
He said that, in contrast, during the previous wave of the Delta outbreak, the COVID-19 patients he treated had "difficulty breathing and low blood oxygen levels."
Many people will need to be hospitalized within a few days.
Within two weeks of the first report of the Omecron variant in southern Africa, other doctors shared similar experiences.
Although it will take several weeks to collect enough data, doctors’ observations and early evidence have provided some clues.
According to the South African National Institute for Communicable Diseases, only 30% of COVID-19 patients hospitalized in recent weeks have severe illness, half the proportion of severe cases in the previous wave of the pandemic; the average length of hospital stay has decreased from 8 days to 2.8 days; and only 3% of recent COVID-19 patients have died, compared to 20% in the early outbreak in South Africa.
Willem Hanekom, director of the Africa Institute for Health Research, cited data from the National Institute for Infectious Diseases and other reports, saying, "Currently, almost all indications suggest that this is a relatively mild disease."
He added, "It's still early, and we need to get data from later stages."
Typically, hospitalizations and deaths occur later in the day, but we've only been in this wave of the pandemic for two weeks.
Meanwhile, scientists around the world are monitoring case numbers and hospitalization rates, while testing the effectiveness of current vaccines and treatments.
Although Delta remains the dominant strain of the coronavirus worldwide, cases of Omekkajong are emerging in dozens of countries, with South Africa being the epicenter of the outbreak.
According to health officials, Gauteng province saw a 400% increase in new cases during the first week of December, with tests showing that the Omega variant accounted for more than 90% of the cases.
