Educational Commentary: What is needed to save abducted children?
If we draw an analogy to the famous public service advertisement slogan "No buying, no killing," then in a favorable environment where there is no demand for "trafficking," collective prevention and control, and nationwide anti-trafficking efforts, would make trafficking unprofitable, risky, and costly, and such crimes would not occur frequently.
Recently, the Anti-Trafficking Office of the Criminal Investigation Bureau of the Ministry of Public Security launched an emergency release platform for information on missing children.
This is an internet information platform created to establish an authoritative channel for releasing information on missing children and to promptly find abducted children.
Upon hearing that the app is called "Reunion," I immediately felt a sense of warmth.
The new technologies are not only "artistic" in name and full of sentiment, but also practical and effective in terms of the proper use of information technology.
The primary goal of law enforcement in combating child trafficking is to find abducted children and protect their personal safety and freedom.
The second step is the trial and punishment of the suspect.
The significance of criminal punishment can be summarized in many broad terms, from individual punishment and social prevention to legal education.
However, before a human trafficking case is solved, the personal safety of the victims should be given priority.
Priorities should be distinguished by their importance and urgency. Under the urgent goal of "searching and rescuing," controversial topics such as "whether child abduction should be punishable by death" can be temporarily set aside for careful discussion; however, the matter of rescuing abducted children cannot wait.
Based on experience in investigating such cases, human traffickers are accustomed to leaving the crime scene as quickly as possible after committing a crime.
Every minute the search for abducted children is delayed means the child may drift further away from their parents, increasing the difficulty of solving the case.
In this context, coming up with effective methods like the "Reunion" platform, which directly helps solve cases and find children, is indeed a pragmatic action.
After all, combating human trafficking is a major task that requires the entire legal system to be mobilized to accomplish it.
Combating crime and protecting the rights of children and parents requires a commitment to "protecting the young and supporting the vulnerable," encompassing everything from improving legislation and ensuring judicial safeguards to meticulous law enforcement.
Furthermore, there is still much that can be done better in preventing child trafficking, from families to society.
For example, a common case is that a family of three is resting at a train station. The parents are fast asleep, and when they wake up, they find that their child is missing.
You can't expect a two-year-old to have enough self-protection skills, but as parents of young children, you should at least have a considerable awareness of protection.
Taking turns to rest or placing the child under safe protection are the most basic measures to prevent child abduction.
From the perspective of the police's crackdown on human trafficking, those who buy trafficked children should also be given attention and punished.
A single illegal act is often just one link in a long chain.
According to my country's Criminal Law, the starting point for the statutory penalty for the crime of child trafficking is five years; in particularly serious cases, the penalty can be death, and property may be confiscated.
With a high starting point for prosecution and a severe maximum penalty, child trafficking is clearly a crime with relatively heavy punishment under the general trend of "lighter penalties".
However, there are still many cases of human trafficking every year.
It is evident that some people have outdated views on raising children and a weak sense of the law.
Legal education for this group should be carried out in tandem.
To effectively control human trafficking, strict law enforcement by the authorities alone is insufficient.
If a market for trafficking exists widely, and traffickers, driven by greed, continue to innovate their trafficking methods, creating a "battle of wits" with law enforcement, the anti-trafficking campaign will inevitably become inefficient.
Therefore, breaking down outdated ideas and popularizing legal knowledge can also help eradicate crimes of child trafficking and buying.
Yang Haodong delivered a speech on the spirit of the Sixth Plenary Session of the 19th CPC Central Committee and the Provincial Party Congress in Malanshan.
Draw strength from the Party's century-long history of struggle.
Hunan Daily, December 10 (All-media reporter Gong Baiwei) – In accordance with the unified arrangements of the Provincial Party Committee, on the morning of December 10, Yang Haodong, member of the Standing Committee of the Provincial Party Committee and Minister of the Publicity Department of the Provincial Party Committee, delivered an interactive lecture at the Malanshan Video Cultural and Creative Park to thoroughly study and implement the spirit of the Sixth Plenary Session of the 19th CPC Central Committee, the spirit of General Secretary Xi Jinping's important speeches, instructions and directives on Hunan, and the spirit of the 12th Hunan Provincial Party Congress.
Yang Haodong, drawing on his own insights and personal experiences, explained the core essence and practical requirements of the spirit of the plenary session from three aspects: ideals and beliefs and original mission, self-revolution and the youthful party, and the party's leaders and theories. He provided a comprehensive and systematic explanation.
He pointed out that we should study the spirit of the plenary session in conjunction with the spirit of General Secretary Xi Jinping’s important speeches, instructions and directives on Hunan and the spirit of the provincial party congress, and integrate them into our learning to enhance our ideological, political and practical awareness of safeguarding the “two establishments” and achieving the “two safeguards”, and unswervingly move forward along the direction guided by General Secretary Xi Jinping.
During the interactive exchange session, representatives from grassroots cadres, enterprises, and youth raised questions about the relationship between the three historical resolutions, how to understand the decisive significance of the "two establishments," how cultural enterprises should grasp the guiding principles, and how young people in the new era can draw strength from the century-long history of the Party. Yang Haodong answered each question in simple language and with vivid examples. He earnestly encouraged young Party members to draw strength from the Party's century-long history of struggle, closely unite around the Party Central Committee, unswervingly follow the Party, and dedicate their youth to fulfilling their responsibilities and commitments.
The number of college graduates in Beijing in 2022 is expected to reach 268,000 - Xinhua News Agency
BEIJING, Dec. 11 (Xinhua) -- The number of college graduates in Beijing in 2022 is expected to reach 268,000, an increase of 16,000 from last year, according to a video conference on employment and entrepreneurship for 2022 college graduates jointly held by the Beijing Municipal Education Commission and the Beijing Municipal Human Resources and Social Security Bureau.
A relevant official from the Beijing Municipal Human Resources and Social Security Bureau stated that the city will deploy its efforts to promote employment for Beijing college graduates by strengthening supply and demand matching, enhancing policy support, expanding employment channels, ensuring assistance for those in need, supporting innovation and entrepreneurship, and improving service efficiency.
Reporters learned that the Beijing Municipal Human Resources and Social Security Bureau will establish a practical platform, increase job supply, proactively contact 40 workplace experience bases for college graduates, visit employers, and integrate demand and job information; it will focus on "six batches," namely, expanding recruitment to public institutions, expanding recruitment to state-owned enterprises, expanding recruitment to grassroots projects, expanding recruitment to the military, expanding employment internships and retention, and expanding entrepreneurship to drive employment; it will implement dynamic management with "one policy per student," recommending no less than five job opportunities to each graduate, and ensuring that 100% of graduates from disadvantaged families who wish to work receive assistance.
