The International Olive Oil Association classifies olive oil into two main categories: virgin olive oil and refined olive oil (Lampante or Refined Olive Oil), with five grades.
Extra virgin olive oil, also known as natural olive oil, is oil obtained by mechanically cold pressing fresh olives and then filtering to remove impurities.
Based on different acidity levels, they can be divided into three grades:
Extra Virgin Olive Oil: This is the highest grade and quality olive oil, a completely natural product.
It has an excellent flavor with a delicate and pleasant herbal aroma and an acidity of no more than 1%.
Fine Virgin Olive Oil: Slightly higher acidity, but not exceeding 2%, with a pure and aromatic flavor.
Ordinary virgin olive oil: The taste and flavor are acceptable, and the acidity does not exceed 3.3%.
Refined olive oil refers to olive oil obtained by refining extra virgin olive oil with an acidity exceeding 3.3%, and is also known as "secondary oil".
Refined olive oil can be divided into two grades:
Regular olive oil: A blend of refined olive oil and a certain proportion of extra virgin olive oil to balance the flavor and color. Its acidity is below 1.5%, and it is a transparent light golden yellow.
Refined olive-pomace oil is olive oil obtained by extracting and refining olive pomace through a solvent extraction process.
If you've seen the grading system, you've probably already noticed that the acidity of olive oil is a very important indicator.
Just like grapes for making wine, olives from different regions and varieties will produce olive oil of different standards.
The best growing region for olives:
The Mediterranean coast has the most suitable soil, temperature, sunshine, air humidity, and rainfall conditions for olive cultivation.
Apart from the Mediterranean coast, it can only be planted sporadically in suitable growing areas in other regions.
Main producing regions (Mediterranean):
Italy, Spain, Greece, Turkey, Portugal, Morocco, Syria, Israel, Tunisia, Algeria, Egypt, Pakistan, Lebanon, and many other countries, as well as Argentina, Peru, South Africa, and other countries with similar climates located at far southern latitudes.
Olive harvesting months:
From March to June each year, olive trees flower and set fruit. From July to October, the fruit begins to develop and ripen, transitioning from green to red, purple, and finally black.
The harvest season for olive oil is from November to February of the following year (freshness is very important).
Nutritional components of olive oil:
Olive oil is rich in monounsaturated fatty acids, namely oleic acid, linoleic acid, and linolenic acid, as well as vitamins A, B, D, E, and K, and antioxidants.
Olive oil is considered the most suitable oil for human nutrition among all oils discovered to date.
The Democracy Summit concludes; Biden says the flame of freedom will never be extinguished.
The online Summit for Democracy, convened by US President Joe Biden and attended by leaders of governments, civil society and private sector from 110 countries around the world, concluded on Friday (December 10).
In his closing remarks, Biden said that the fire of freedom burns in the hearts of everyone in the world and that authoritarian regimes can never extinguish it.
He also stated that he plans to hold the second global "Democracy Summit" next year.
Taiwanese government representative Audrey Tang and Nathan Law, a Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist currently in exile in the UK, also spoke at the summit on the second day.
Biden said: "We know how difficult the job is before us."
But we also know that we can meet the challenges, because, as I have said before, as this summit has demonstrated, the democratic world is everywhere.
Authoritarian regimes can never extinguish the flame of freedom; it burns in the hearts of people all over the world.
Biden also stated that defending democracy requires the collective effort of the entire society.
He said: "As leaders of government, we have a responsibility to listen to our citizens, strengthen the safeguards of democracy, promote reform, achieve transparent and accountable governance, and better withstand the buffers and shocks of authoritarianism, as well as those who seek power nakedly above the public good."
The second day of the "Democracy Summit" focused on defending human rights, consolidating democracy and confronting authoritarianism, and fighting against digital authoritarianism and affirming democratic values.
This day coincides with "International Human Rights Day".
In his opening remarks that day, UN Secretary-General Guterres also stated that the cause of democracy faces challenges globally, particularly those brought about by emerging digital technologies.
He said: "Now is the time to reaffirm shared values ​​and positions, as well as democratic resilience."
This requires deepening social dialogue, addressing inequality, combating corruption, updating the social contract, investing in quality education, and expanding opportunities for women and girls.
This also necessitates a firm condemnation of all forms of populism, nativism, and extremism, including the exploitation of all the tools available to the technological revolution.
Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Nathan Law addressed the summit via pre-recorded video, reminding participants to continue to pay attention to the human rights situation in Hong Kong and among China's ethnic minorities such as Uyghurs and Tibetans.
He said: "The world has long accepted China's rise without establishing a mechanism to hold it accountable."
This is why politicians and civil society leaders must work together.
We must use all the resources we have to ensure that the restoration of democracy is our top priority.
Nathan Law also called on the free world to unite against the threat posed by the Chinese Communist Party.
He said: "Perhaps some of you are afraid of offending General Secretary Xi Jinping, perhaps some of you do not want to lose the Chinese market, perhaps some of you do not realize the threat (the CCP) poses to our democratic values."
And that's why we failed.
This is why we must change.
During a roundtable discussion on "Combating Digital Authoritarianism and Affirming Democratic Values," Audrey Tang, Minister without Portfolio of the Executive Yuan of Taiwan, released a "National Statement" via video, emphasizing that Taiwan stands at the forefront of the fight against authoritarianism and authoritarianism.
He also shared his experience on how to combat the COVID-19 pandemic through information transparency and building mutual trust.
He said: "As democracy in Taiwan is still in its infancy, we have always stood firmly at the forefront of the global fight against authoritarianism, and played a leading role in promoting global freedom, democracy and human rights."
During the pandemic, authoritarian governments around the world have justified human rights violations in the name of public health and collective interests, and global democracy is showing signs of regression.
However, in Taiwan, we can control the epidemic without lockdowns and defeat misinformation without removing content from online platforms.
On the second day of the "Democracy Summit," the U.S. Treasury Department announced sanctions against 15 individuals and 10 entities from several countries, including China and North Korea, for serious human rights abuses, and imposed investment restrictions on a Chinese company found to have used surveillance technology to assist in human rights abuses.
