I want to try tennis, but I'm afraid I won't be able to stick with it, so I want to find a place with a reasonable price to practice on first.
Unfriendly; in fact, price is often proportional to friendliness. If you can't tell the difference, then expensive rackets are usually more user-friendly than cheaper ones. These "entry-level rackets" are actually industrial garbage.
They have very low strength, and when the ball hits the racket, the vibration is very large. Hard balls can't withstand it, and even experts have difficulty controlling them.
Their logic and subtext is—tennis is so difficult, we know you can't learn it, and we know you're unwilling to buy expensive ones, so we'll give you a cheap one to fool you. You'll play it twice and then you won't play anymore, so the racket is cheap and you won't feel bad about it.
When you can truly distinguish between good and bad, it means you've made progress. Then you can come back to me and buy the more expensive items, and I'll make money twice.
I suggest spending a similar amount of money to buy a decent used racket, such as Prince or Dunlop. These two brands are not well-known enough that even good rackets don't fetch a high price. A new racket costs around 500 or 600 yuan, and a used one costs around 200 yuan. Isn't it great to have the enjoyment of a racket worth a thousand yuan?
