Xinhua Media+ | Beijing Youth Ice Hockey League Ignites Enthusiasm for the Winter Olympics - Xinhua Net
On December 11, Pang Yaotian (center), a player for the Beijing Dream ING team, shoots during the match.
On that day, the 2021-2022 Beijing Youth Ice Hockey Club League continued to be held at various ice rinks in Beijing.
This year's league is divided into a regular season and playoffs. The participating athletes are aged from U6 to U18, and the groups are divided into competitive group and selection group, attracting nearly 3,600 players from 256 teams across the city.
After more than ten years of development, the Beijing Youth Ice Hockey Club League has become a platform for Beijing's youth ice hockey enthusiasts to hone their skills, make friends, and provide outstanding players for Beijing's youth ice hockey teams and youth teams.
The league leverages its role in promoting youth ice hockey in Beijing, fueling enthusiasm for the Winter Olympics ice hockey, and laying the foundation for the development of ice hockey in Beijing in the post-Winter Olympics era.
Girl uses archery target to raise money for her sister: "Thinking it's just a minor injury, it's not so bad" - Xinhua News Agency
A girl stands in front of a large wooden board in Wulin Square, Hangzhou. The board reads "Human target, ten yuan per arrow".
Yesterday morning, a photo of a Hangzhou girl acting as a "target" to raise funds for her sister went viral on social media.
The photo shows a girl standing in front of a large wooden board slightly taller than a person in Wulin Square, Hangzhou. The board reads "Human target, ten yuan per arrow," indicating that passersby can use the bow and arrow to shoot after paying.
This behavior sparked heated discussions among netizens.
Last night, a spokesperson for the Hangzhou Public Security Bureau's Xiacheng Branch confirmed to a reporter from the Beijing News that the police confirmed the girl's extreme actions were to raise money for her sister, but such behavior is not commendable. After being warned, the girl left the local police station yesterday.
Girl reprimanded for soliciting donations on the street using "arrow targets"
In the widely circulated photos, a long-haired girl is standing in front of a large wooden board in a "个" shape. The board has the words "Human target, ten yuan per arrow" written on it in black ink. Another board in front of her has her bank account number, WeChat account, Alipay account, etc. written on it.
The image sparked controversy after it was posted online.
Some netizens believe this is an "attention-grabbing begging act," while many others express sympathy for it.
"We discovered the situation around 10 a.m. on the 23rd when we were patrolling near the square. By then, there were already quite a few onlookers."
Police officers from the Tianshui Police Station, which is near the scene of the incident, told local media that there were two girls selling goods at the stall, both around 20 years old and dressed in a youthful and attractive manner.
Among them, the girl acting as the "human target" kept crying, begging passersby to play the game; another girl on the side helped by shouting that her friend's sister had leukemia and urgently needed surgery money, asking everyone for help.
"We contacted the local police in Guizhou and learned that the girl was raising funds for her sister's leukemia treatment."
Last night, a spokesperson for the Hangzhou Public Security Bureau's Xiacheng Branch told a reporter from the Beijing News that the girl's name is Ji Jiali, and she was raising funds for her sister, Ji Jiayan.
However, since the treatment still requires more than 300,000 yuan, and they couldn't think of a good way to raise funds, they resorted to this action.
He said that throughout the process, one girl acted as the target and the other assisted, but they did not participate in the shooting. No one was seen shooting arrows during the process; some people just watched and took photos, which were then posted on Weibo.
After investigation by the public security department, the police determined that the bow and arrows used were not subject to control.
The person in charge stated, "We do not advocate this kind of attention-grabbing fundraising method."
After being warned by the police, she has left the police station.
