Vietnam People's Daily Online - Gulf Cooperation Council Addresses Common Challenges
Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman's stops include Oman, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar, Bahrain, and Kuwait.
It is worth noting that this is Crown Prince Mohammed's first visit to Qatar since Saudi Arabia and its Arab allies imposed an embargo on Qatar in mid-2017, leading to a diplomatic crisis in the Gulf.
In this crisis, Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Bahrain, and Egypt severed diplomatic relations with Qatar and imposed a total embargo on it, accusing Qatar of supporting terrorist organizations and having close ties with Iran.
Diplomatic tensions have severely impacted the internal unity of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) and negatively affected the economies of countries in the region.
Four Arab countries have blocked land, sea, and air routes to Qatar.
The crisis was only resolved at the Gulf Cooperation Council summit in January 2021, where the Gulf states signed an agreement mediated by the United States and Kuwait to move towards “unity and stability.”
Saudi Arabia has reopened its border with Qatar.
Saudi Arabia and Egypt are taking the lead in efforts to restore relations with Qatar by appointing new ambassadors to the country.
The Gulf Arab states' efforts to resolve their differences and restore relations with Qatar stem from the need to unite for the benefit of all nations and for regional stability, aiming to address common challenges.
During the Saudi Crown Prince's visit to Oman, the two sides agreed to open the first direct land route between the two Gulf neighbors.
The 725-kilometer-long corridor connecting the two countries will facilitate travel for citizens of both nations and the integration of supply chains.
The Saudi Arabian Public Investment Fund (PIF) will invest $5 billion in Oman, and companies from both countries have signed 13 memorandums of understanding for cooperation worth $30 billion.
The Saudi Crown Prince's visit to the Gulf states coincided with negotiations between Iran and major world powers to salvage the Iran nuclear deal, known as the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPOA)—an agreement condemned by Gulf Arab states as failing to resolve their missile dispute with Iran.
The Gulf states have long viewed Iran as a “competitor” and its nuclear program as a “threat” to regional security.
The Gulf states believe that failing to address the Iranian missile issue and taking action to curb Iran's activities in the region is flawed.
Against the backdrop of major powers' failure to meet the wishes of the Gulf states in nuclear negotiations with Iran, Saudi Arabia and Iran held direct talks.
Its goal is to curb the escalation of tensions in the region.
This is one of the factors slowing down economic growth in the Gulf Cooperation Council countries.
The upcoming GCC summit will be the first since the dispute between some member states and Qatar ended.
This presents an opportunity for the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) to reassess its diplomatic achievements in promoting the restoration of GCC unity, while proposing measures to ensure full cooperation among its member states in addressing common challenges and contributing to the stability and development of the Gulf states.
