Guangxi University Students Can Take a Leave of Absence to Start a Business for Up to 5 Years - Xinhua News Agency
NANNING, May 19 (Xinhua) -- According to the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region Education Department, universities in Guangxi will implement a flexible academic system in the future, extending the leave of absence period for college students. The leave of absence for entrepreneurship can be extended by 2 to 5 years beyond the original academic period, and the leave of absence for entrepreneurship can be considered as practical education time.
To promote the entrepreneurship and innovation capabilities of college students, the education and human resources departments in Guangxi have joined forces to build entrepreneurship platforms, construct more off-campus practical teaching bases, university science parks, college student entrepreneurship parks, and entrepreneurship incubation bases, providing external support for college students' entrepreneurship.
According to the requirements, by 2020, the area of ​​innovation and entrepreneurship practice bases in universities should reach more than 3,000 square meters for undergraduate schools and more than 2,000 square meters for vocational colleges.
The government encourages universities to establish innovation and entrepreneurship credits and gives priority to supporting students who excel in innovation and entrepreneurship practice to change their major.
University teachers should spend at least two months every two years working in industry enterprises to improve their awareness and ability in innovation and entrepreneurship education.
The Education Department of Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region requires all universities in Guangxi to thoroughly implement the Undergraduate Innovation and Entrepreneurship Training Program, striving to ensure that every university student participates in an innovation and entrepreneurship training program during their time at university.
Universities should actively organize students to participate in innovation and entrepreneurship competitions at all levels and provide financial support.
NEWS GOV-MO: University of Macau confers honorary doctorates on 7 distinguished individuals
The University of Macau held the “2021 Honorary Degree and Higher Degree Conferment Ceremony” today (11th), conferring honorary doctoral degrees to Liu Zunyi, Chen Kaixian, Nakamura Shuji, Li Lanjuan, Li Xiaoliang, Zhu Lilan and Jiang Zhaohui in recognition of their outstanding achievements and significant contributions to the development of society and education.
At the award ceremony, the Chief Executive and Secretary for Social Affairs and Culture, Ao Ieong U, representing the University of Macau Council Chairman Lam Kam Seng and University of Macau Rector Song Yong Hua, conferred an honorary doctorate.
Professor Liu Zunyi was awarded an honorary doctorate in education; Professor Chen Kaixian was awarded an honorary doctorate in science; Professor Nakamura Shuji was awarded an honorary doctorate in science; Professor Li Lanjuan was awarded an honorary doctorate in science; Professor Li Xiaoliang was awarded an honorary doctorate in business administration; Professor Zhu Lilan was awarded an honorary doctorate in science; and Ms. Jiang Zhaohui was awarded an honorary doctorate in science.
In her address, Ouyang Yu first extended her warmest congratulations and highest respect to the seven outstanding individuals who were awarded honorary doctorates. They have achieved remarkable success in their respective fields and made outstanding contributions to the development of the country and the progress of the world. At the same time, Ouyang Yu expressed her sincerest blessings to the graduates and their parents, and also paid heartfelt tribute to the university's dedicated and academically excellent faculty and staff.
When reading the eulogy for Liu Zunyi, Professor Sun Yifeng of the Faculty of Humanities at the University of Macau stated that Professor Liu Zunyi is a world-renowned economist, known for his outstanding academic achievements and forward-thinking educational philosophy.
In addition to his achievements in economic development, economic growth, and the East Asian economy, he was also a visionary education leader.
In short, he has made outstanding achievements in many fields.
When reading the eulogy for Shuji Nakamura, Sun Yifeng stated that Professor Shuji Nakamura was a pioneer in sustainable energy technology.
He was one of the three winners of the 2014 Nobel Prize in Physics for inventing the blue light-emitting diode (LED).
Professor Nakamura's invention not only revolutionized the lighting industry, but also spurred the development of white light-emitting diodes, which are now widely used in daily life and industrial production, making a significant contribution to human well-being.
When reading the eulogy for Li Lanjuan, Sun Yifeng said that Professor Li Lanjuan, as a pioneer in China's artificial liver industry, created the unique and effective Li's artificial liver system, which achieved a major breakthrough in the treatment of severe hepatitis and liver failure, and significantly reduced the mortality rate of liver failure.
In the fight against COVID-19, the "four resistances and two balances" plan proposed by her and her team, along with the three major technologies they brought—artificial liver, microecology, and stem cells—significantly improved the cure rate for severe cases.
When reading Li Xiaoliang's eulogy, Sun Yifeng said that Professor Li Xiaoliang laid the foundation for innovative research in operations management, shaped the way of thinking about supply chain theory and practice, and completely changed business models around the world.
Li Xiaoliang is known for popularizing the concept of the bullwhip effect in operations management and for exploring measures to address this phenomenon.
Today, amid the pandemic and tense economic situation, the whiplash effect is becoming increasingly prominent in various countries, causing severe disruption to supply chains.
Li Xiaoliang's visionary research is like sending charcoal in snowy weather, helping the industry cope with difficulties and thus bringing enormous social value.
When reading Zhu Lilan's eulogy, Sun Yifeng said that in her scientific research, she discovered a groundbreaking and innovative staining technique for sample preparation, which has earned her a high reputation among scientific peers at home and abroad.
With her extraordinary scientific and technological achievements, she has been awarded important honors such as Academician of the International Eurasian Academy of Sciences, and her brilliant achievements have earned her the high status she deserves in the world's scientific and technological arena.
When reading the eulogy for Professor Chen Kaixian, Chen Xin, acting director of the Institute of Chinese Medical Sciences at the University of Macau, said that Professor Chen Kaixian has been engaged in drug research and development for more than 40 years. His outstanding scientific achievements and important contributions to the country, Macau, the University of Macau and national key laboratories have earned him a high international status and reputation.
His positive role in promoting the development of traditional Chinese medicine in Macao and the Greater Bay Area fully demonstrates his sense of mission to contribute to the national strategy for the development of medicine.
When reading the eulogy for Jiang Zhaohui, Professor Xu Chengzhong, Dean of the Faculty of Science and Technology at the University of Macau, stated that Ms. Jiang Zhaohui has participated in the research and development of more than 15 major inventions and patents related to storage virtualization, navigation, file systems and power management, all of which are highly practical, widely used and improve the convenience of human life.
As an accomplished inventor, Ms. Jiang often simplifies complex technologies and theories, making them accessible to the general public.
Finally, Chen Kaixian, as the representative of the honorary doctorates, read out a speech of thanks.
He was pleased to see that the medical and pharmaceutical industry in Macao and the Greater Bay Area has set a good example: from the first national key laboratory for quality research of Chinese medicine established by the University of Macau to the vigorous development of traditional Chinese medicine in the Greater Bay Area, the University of Macau has made a great contribution to integrating outstanding talents in the field of traditional Chinese medicine in the Greater Bay Area.
In addition, he believes that the University of Macau’s management team has vision and foresight, not only providing students with fertile ground for research in academia, but also contributing many responsible talents to society.
He was honored to have the opportunity to exchange ideas and cooperate with the University of Macau, and expressed his sincere congratulations on the achievements the University of Macau has made in recent years.
