Asian American groups complain about admissions discrimination by three Ivy League schools, including Yale - Xinhua News Agency
WASHINGTON, May 23 (Xinhua) -- More than 130 Asian American groups filed complaints with the U.S. Department of Education and the Department of Justice on Tuesday, protesting that three Ivy League universities—Yale University, Brown University, and Dartmouth College—discriminate against Asian American applicants in their admissions process.
The Asian American Education Alliance, which spearheaded the complaint, held a press conference in Washington that day.
At the press conference, Zhao Yukong, chairman of the group, said that in the past 10 years, the number of Asian applicants who meet the admission requirements of top American universities has increased exponentially, but the proportion of Asians in these three top American universities has remained at roughly the same level.
Numerous studies have shown that these universities have “long-standing and systematically discriminated against Asian applicants” in their so-called “holistic” admissions process.
Zhao Yukong explained that a 2014 study by Sanders and other scholars showed that, relative to the number of applicants, Asian Americans had the lowest admission rate among all ethnic groups in these three universities.
Data from the U.S. Department of Education also shows that among all Ivy League schools, Brown University and Dartmouth College have the lowest admission rates for Asian American students, while Yale University and Brown University have implemented de facto racial quotas for Asian American applicants for more than 20 years.
Zhao Yukong told Xinhua News Agency that they hope that after submitting the appeal, the U.S. Department of Education and the Department of Justice will launch an investigation and take measures to stop these universities from continuing to discriminate against Asian Americans in admissions after determining the facts.
They also hope that the universities that have been complained about will take this issue seriously and change their admissions policies for Asian Americans.
The three universities that have been complained about have not yet responded.
The Asian American Education Alliance was founded in 2015 after it filed a complaint against Harvard University for admissions discrimination, but the U.S. Department of Education did not accept the complaint on procedural grounds.
In addition to Chinese American groups, the petition also included educational groups of Indian, Korean, Japanese, and Pakistani descent.
