3,200 newborn babies in Sabah were denied birth certificates due to a shortage of specially made anti-counterfeiting paper.
(Kota Kinabalu, 11th) The Sabah National Registration Department said that due to the depletion of its special anti-counterfeiting paper stock, it has been unable to issue birth certificates to newborns since the beginning of October, affecting a total of 3,200 people to date.
However, the bureau chief, Kairou Aminus, assured that the information of all babies who have applied for birth certificates has been recorded in the system and will be reissued once the anti-counterfeiting paper arrives next week.
At a press conference, he addressed a report by an online media outlet that the Sabah Daily newspaper had been experiencing printing problems for 10 months.
He said the problem had emerged two months ago, and Sarawak was facing the same issue.
"One reason is that Chinese manufacturers producing special anti-counterfeiting paper have been affected by the pandemic, leading to delays in the delivery of goods to our country."
He explained that the anti-counterfeiting paper used in Sabah newspapers is different from that used in other regions, so it is not possible to borrow stock from other states.
Khairul Aminus revealed that the latest batch of anti-counterfeiting paper arrived in Kuala Lumpur on the 6th of this month and was subsequently handed over to the printing company on the 8th for partial printing.
"The department will send personnel to Kuala Lumpur next Thursday to collect the documents. Upon returning to Sabah, they will immediately proceed with the final printing stage. It is estimated that the documents will be delivered to the applicants in about two more working days (December 20th)."
"We will notify applicants to collect their birth certificates from local branch offices."
He added that Sabah has issued 24,801 birth certificates so far this year.
