Don't scare people at the starting line - Xinhua News Agency
When browsing book fairs, one can often feel the popularity of self-help books.
Many self-help books today promote the "best principle"—that is, first assume or imply that you can "do it," and then tell you "what" you need to do.
This means that we have skipped over the most important and fundamental aspect: "how to do it".
This is why these books all share a common characteristic—either go all out and do your best, or do nothing at all; it's either 100 or 0; either climb Mount Tai or stay where you are.
This "best principle" is so correct that anyone would agree it's absolutely right, but 99% of people would be scared off at the starting line.
This theory advocates a path of "you must make a firm decision, start anew, and make a 180-degree turn," which is precisely the fatal weakness of many people.
For someone who is conservative, clings to old ways, and refuses to change, shouting "You need to change" in their ear is undoubtedly self-deception and a waste of breath.
Most people hesitate and struggle to make a decision when faced with the word "change"; or they may make a decision to "change" on a whim and take the first step bravely, but often the good times don't last long and they give up after a short while, making it difficult to sustain.
Mr. Ma Sanli's famous crosstalk performance "Starting Tomorrow" is a classic example that most vividly expresses this "universal human nature".
The biggest problem with the "best principle" is that the threshold is too high. It often exceeds the ability limits of ordinary people, leaving the vast majority of people "sighing in despair".
Perhaps the "second-best principle" is a way to help more ordinary people achieve relative success.
The core of the "second-best principle" lies in "lowering the threshold"—it encourages a theory of "accumulating small victories into a big victory," that is, if you can't do 100, doing 1 is fine: because 1 is always greater than 0; if you can't climb Mount Tai, climbing the small sand dune in front of your house is fine, because that's still better than standing still.
In short, doing something is always better than doing nothing.
Because the threshold has been significantly lowered, it has become more possible for ordinary people to persevere, and as long as you persevere, the probability of success will also increase.
The path to success by following the "second-best principle" is simply a bit longer.
In conclusion, while the "best principle" claims to enable everyone to succeed, it ultimately only motivates a minority; whereas the "second-best principle" can effectively motivate more people and benefit as many as possible.
