I just saw an article about menstruation, it was too long.
Let me explain this to men who don't know.
Most girls will suddenly experience their first period sometime between the ages of 13 and 15, and will stop menstruating around the age of 50.
Provided I remain in good health, I will have my period more regularly, once a month.
However, it's not so predictable that it's regular. The tolerance is about a week, so you need to prepare in advance. Sometimes, bad luck can cause things to go wrong (suddenly several days ahead of schedule).
The duration, amount of bleeding, and severity of menstrual cramps vary from person to person. Some people experience bleeding for three days, while others experience it for a week. Some people have light bleeding, while others experience heavy bleeding. Some people have no symptoms, while others are in so much pain that they need to be taken away by ambulance. Menstrual cramps can change over time, and not having pain before does not mean you will never have pain again.
My period is uncontrollable; I bleed for 24 hours a day from the start to the end. All I can do is use sanitary napkins or tampons to absorb the blood and prevent it from getting on my clothes and chairs.
Menstrual cramps are mainly caused by the secretion of prostaglandins. Taking ibuprofen at the beginning of menstruation, before menstrual cramps occur, can effectively relieve the pain during that month. Taking it after menstrual cramps have started is not very effective.
Diarrhea is common before menstruation due to uterine congestion and excessive release of prostaglandins.
If you have diarrhea for no apparent reason around the time of your period, your period will usually start within two days.
It's best to change sanitary napkins every two to three hours, otherwise bacteria can easily grow. Excluding sleep time, in the worst case, you need to change them 6 times a day, 7 days a month, which is 42 pads. If you add the amount you prepare in advance, you might have 50 pads. It's not about using one pad per month.
(This should be corrected: tampons do not need to be changed frequently, about once every five or six hours is sufficient, and at most once every eight hours.)
Hormonal fluctuations during menstruation can make you more irritable, and ovulation can also cause mood swings due to changes in hormones. It's just unlucky, as your body seems to be giving you trouble.
However, official crime rate data shows that women have a high ability to control their emotions and do not use emotional problems as an excuse.
It's not just blood that's flowing out; it also includes shed uterine lining.
The uterine lining is thinnest after menstruation ends, and then gradually thickens. You can think of the uterus as a house, where a new house is built each month (the lining thickens) to prepare for guests. If no guests come, the lining is completely removed (menstrual blood is expelled), and a new house is built the following month, and the cycle repeats.
Menstruation is very inconvenient. For decades, I have been bleeding for several days every month for 24 hours, and I also have abdominal and back pain. Who would want that?
However, a person is born because his mother has menstruated. Menstruation is to prepare the house for you to live in for 10 months when you first come into this world. Everyone should thank their mother for having regular and healthy menstruation.
In the past, women faced a lot of suppression, and society brainwashed them into thinking that things were dirty and shameful. Everyone believed that was the case, but times have changed.
If anyone finds menstruation disgusting, or thinks that the preparations a woman's body makes for conceiving life disgusting, and shouldn't say it in public, girls, stand up and stop thinking like that. And men who have never experienced it, will never experience it in their lives, and don't really understand it, don't be so ungrateful and ungrateful. How can you face your mother with such an attitude? How can you have the nerve to want your own child?
Finally, ladies, try tampons, they're really good.
