Is numbness in my feet after soaking in a foot bath due to an electrical leak?
Choosing the right foot bath basin can have excellent foot therapy and health benefits. Today, Gome's editor will answer this question and hope it will be helpful to our readers.
As people become more health-conscious, foot baths are becoming increasingly popular with consumers, and a wide variety of products at different price points have emerged in the market, ranging from a little over one hundred yuan to over a thousand yuan, giving consumers a great deal of choice.
According to relevant data, health-related home appliances such as foot baths are selling like hotcakes compared to traditional home appliances. However, there are no specific industry standards for foot baths, which poses certain safety hazards.
"Soaking your feet in electrified water is just too dangerous!"
Mr. Li told reporters that he recently bought a foot bath basin as a birthday gift for his father, but his father felt numbness in his feet while soaking them.
Mr. Li initially thought it was caused by the vibration function of the foot bath, but he didn't expect that even after turning off the vibration function, his father still felt numbness in the soles of his feet.
Mr. Li tested the water with a test pen, and it lit up. To his surprise, he discovered that the water in the foot bath was electrified.
He later contacted the merchant, who was quite accommodating. Although he returned the foot bath, Mr. Li was still unhappy.
He discovered that the foot bath basin, which has been popular for a long time, currently lacks clear and detailed industry regulations regarding its maximum temperature setting, suitable user groups, and materials that ensure its safety.
However, foot bath basins generally do not have electrical problems, but it cannot be ruled out that a few products may not have been strictly inspected at the factory.
Therefore, choose a split-type foot bath basin when purchasing.
With water and electricity separated, there are no safety hazards.
You can also use a test pen to check freely.
The 13th Hunan Provincial Tea Expo Opens - Viewpoint Headlines - Hunan Daily Website - Huasheng Online
Hunan Daily, December 10 (Reporter Zhang Shangwu, Hu Panpan, Correspondent Liu Xiaoling, Photographer Li Jian) ​​– This morning, the 13th Hunan Tea Industry Expo and Xinhua Black Tea Promotion Conference were held at the Hunan International Convention and Exhibition Center. The event showcased the tea industry, innovated tea technology, promoted tea culture, and accelerated efforts to achieve the goal of a 100 billion yuan tea industry.
Hou Shunli, Vice Chairman of the Board of Directors of the All China Federation of Supply and Marketing Cooperatives, and Ye Hongzhuan, Vice Chairman of the Standing Committee of the Provincial People's Congress, attended the opening ceremony.
At the opening ceremony, Professor Liu Zhonghua, an academician of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, solemnly introduced: The origin of Hunan black tea is in Xinhua, and the rise of black tea has injected new impetus into "colorful Hunan tea".
In recent years, the Provincial Party Committee and the Provincial Government have vigorously supported the development of the tea industry, promoted the construction of a 100 billion yuan Hunan tea industry, and formed a development pattern of "three Hunan rivers and five colorful teas".
The tea industry in the province has increased innovation, with major tea categories such as green tea, black tea, and red tea taking turns to promote development. Major tea-producing areas have promoted the integration of tea and tourism, which has boosted the income of tea farmers.
Fortune changes, and black tea is making its comeback.
Tea experts in the province say that after harvesting green tea, tea farmers can also harvest black tea and dark tea, ensuring income for tea farmers throughout the year and leading to a sharp increase in the output value of tea gardens.
At the opening ceremony, provincial leaders presented plaques to the fourth batch of enterprises authorized to use the "Hunan Black Tea" trademark, with Xinhua proudly receiving the title of "Source of Hunan Black Tea".
At the Xinhua Black Tea Exhibition Hall, a Fujian tea merchant took a liking to a high-mountain tea called "Binglichun" and immediately placed an order.
Wang Zhun, secretary-general of the provincial tea association, said happily that the current epidemic and other factors have more or less affected the tea market, but the tea expo has many highlights.
Xinhua black tea, with its distinctive red hue, is imbued with the essence of tea culture, attracting a large customer base and boosting trade, ushering in a new spring for Hunan's tea industry.
