Metaphysics refers to the study of questions that cannot be answered directly through perception, using rational reasoning and logic.
Metaphysics is the fundamental principle of philosophy, which aims to explain the basic nature of existence and the world.
The Chinese translation "形而上学" (xíng ér shàng xué) is taken from the phrase "形而上者谓之道，形而下者谓之器" (xíng ér shàng zhě wèi zhī dào, xíng ér xià zhě wèi zhī qì) in the Book of Changes (易经•系辞传上), translated by the Japanese scholar Inoue Tetsujiro (Meiji era) from the word "metaphysic".
Branches of metaphysics include ontology, natural theology, and related issues.
Ontology is "the study of which terms represent real, existing entities and which terms merely represent concepts."
Metaphysical naturalism refers to the denial of the existence of God.
Its theoretical basis is the concept that all phenomena can be explained by natural reasons, which was proposed by philosophers who support science and evolution.
Methodological naturalism refers to a research method that makes no mention of God.
Philosophy of mind is a branch of philosophy that studies the nature of consciousness and its relationship with the body (especially the brain).
Dualism and monism are the two main schools of thought that discuss the relationship between mind and body.
Epistemology is a branch of philosophy that explores the nature, origin, and scope of knowledge.
Ethics is the discipline that systematically reflects on and studies human moral life; here, morality is defined as all behavioral norms recognized by a group of people or a culture.
It is mainly divided into metaethics (abstractly studying the essence of ethical theories or critiques) and normative ethics (judging various different moral views and providing moral guidelines for right or wrong behavior).
It studies what kind of moral codes of conduct people should follow, applied ethics (the academic study that applies ethical theories to real-life situations, including bioethics, political ethics, etc.), and descriptive ethics (collecting information about how people live and summarizing from observed patterns).
Its examination of ethics does not start from preconceived theories, but rather investigates the actual choices made and observed by moral agents, examining all the moral factors that contribute to these choices, and exploring the ethical views held by social groups.
The history of ethics includes Greek and Roman ethics and medieval Christian ethics.
Part One: Humanist ethical thought, represented by Vara and Montaigne, among others.
Part Two: The ethical thought of the Reformation, represented by Calvin.
Part Three: Political Ethics, represented by Machiavelli and others; Modern Ethics (17th-18th centuries: British Empiricist Ethics, represented by Hume, etc.; 17th-18th centuries: Continental Rationalist Ethics, represented by Spinoza, etc.; 18th century: French Enlightenment Ethics, represented by Voltaire, etc.; 18th-19th centuries: German Academic Ethics, represented by Kant and Hegel, etc.; 18th-19th centuries: British Utilitarian Ethics, represented by Bentham and Siegfried, etc.; 19th century: British Evolutionary Ethics, represented by Spencer and Huxley, etc.; Late 19th century: German Neo-Kantian Ethics, represented by Licker, etc.; Late 19th century: Neo-Hegelian Ethics, represented by Thomas Hill Green, etc.); Transitional Ethics (Irrationalist Ethics, represented by Kierkegaard, Schopenhauer, and Nietzsche, etc.).
Logic is a discipline that studies the principles and standards of effective reasoning and proof.
Logic typically consists of three parts: inductive reasoning, abductive reasoning, and deductive reasoning, and can be divided into formal logic and informal logic.
Aesthetics is a discipline that studies the nature and meaning of beauty.
