Ding Zilin: To a Friend.
I would like to express my heartfelt gratitude to all my friends for the humanitarian assistance they have provided over the long period of more than 30 years since the passing of our loved ones, especially the assistance that has continued uninterrupted since I made a personal appeal for humanitarian aid to friends at home and abroad in early 1994.
The parents of the vast majority of the victims have now passed away, and the orphans have grown up, started their own families, and found employment.
It was your righteous act that helped us, the families who suffered, through the most difficult time.
The COVID-19 pandemic is currently raging around the world, and most of the donors are already in retirement age.
Therefore, I earnestly request that you cease the humanitarian donations to our bereaved families—the Tiananmen Mothers group. This humanitarian aid activity should have come to a perfect end long ago.
I will always remember your kindness and firmly believe that your righteous act will be remembered in history.
For various reasons, this is the only way I can express my wishes. Please understand!
Please accept my heartfelt blessings.
Tao Ye's note: Please allow me to take this opportunity to give a brief introduction to the 32-year history of humanitarian aid work by the Federation of Chinese Americans and Scholars in the United States (IFCSS) and the Minnesota Chinese Democracy Foundation (MCDF).
In the course of humanitarian aid work, the All-American Chinese Students and Scholars Association and the Minnesota Chinese Democracy Foundation are two parallel organizations, and there is often overlap in the implementation of their projects.
(Apple Daily photo: The Tiananmen Mothers website is managed by Tao Ye.) pic.twitter.com/UxID9ZGjzm
Relief funds often fail to reach the families of those who perished in the June Fourth Incident.
In 1994, at Teacher Ding's suggestion, the "Tiananmen Mothers" established a special group to coordinate and be responsible for the receipt and distribution of humanitarian aid funds.
In 1998, the MCDF established the "June 4th Orphans Education Fund". After 11 years of implementation, in 2009, after all the June 4th orphans had graduated from university, the MCDF established the "June 4th Orphans and Impoverished Elderly Relief Fund", which continues to be implemented to this day.
The funds for these projects mainly come from campus and community donations from the Tiananmen Square protests of 1989, from generous individual donations, and are supported by the Brother University Democracy Foundation.
Since 2018, it has also received support from the Laogai Research Foundation.
Last year, after 31 years, the families of the victims of the June 4th Incident finally received a portion of the donations raised in Hong Kong in the name of June 4th.
During this period, Human Rights in China also independently carried out their humanitarian aid projects.
We understand that Professor Ding's decision to halt the June 4th donations was for the sake of the donors. We are indeed all retired elderly people, and our income is not as abundant as it was before retirement. Therefore, we would like to express our gratitude to Professor Ding for his letter "To Friends".
We will respect the families' decision to terminate the project within two years and resume it immediately if necessary.
We express our gratitude and respect to all those courageous and righteous individuals who have consistently and generously donated to deliver humanitarian aid over the years, risking their own safety.
