A programming newbie who wants to share their personal experiences.
If you're planning to enter this industry, you can choose to find a place for training. But if you don't have this idea, it's best to learn on your own, since training costs a lot of money and takes six months to learn.
However, if you plan to get into this industry, training is indeed a very good choice, especially for those with very weak self-discipline.
If you have strong self-discipline, you can choose to learn on your own, but it will be quite tiring.
Of course, choosing a good training institution is very important.
First, you need to look at the institution's teaching staff. If the teaching staff is not strong enough, then the training institution is meaningless. Of course, some newly opened training institutions do not have particularly strong teaching staff.
Secondly, research the training institution before making a choice. It would be best to find out about the students who graduated from the institution, since only the students themselves know the true quality of the institution and whether the courses are good or bad.
Hello, actually I don't know how to answer your question because I haven't provided any information about your specific situation. And learning is very much related to one's own circumstances.
For example, your major, age, the language you want to learn, and even the city you live in will all be related to the industry you study or want to work in.
If you are a student and have not yet graduated, or if you have already graduated with a computer science degree, I personally recommend self-study if you have enough time. This is the most efficient and cost-effective method. There are many good offline and online training institutions now, but they are expensive and require a lot of time, generally 3-6 months of intensive training.
However, if it's one of the situations I described, self-study is very convenient. There are many free learning resources online now, or you can find a lot of training resources on Bilibili. If you don't know how to find resources, you can contact me through my profile to get free resources or detailed consultation.
In addition, there are some classic books that can be studied in conjunction with videos.
If you are not a computer science major but can afford the financial and time commitment to learn, then I recommend attending a training institution. This way, learning won't be too strenuous, the teachers will explain things in detail, and there will be someone to answer your questions. In addition, it will also help with learning planning and supervision.
Moreover, many training institutions now sign employment agreements and offer internal referral slots, recommending students to companies after they complete the training. This saves a lot of trouble in the job interview process later on.
These are my thoughts. As I don't know your specific situation, my explanation is only general and not detailed. If you have any other questions, please feel free to contact me for further discussion.
