Chinese and Saudi curators jointly host Saudi Arabia's first contemporary art biennial - Xinhua News Agency
Riyadh, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia's first contemporary art biennial, the Diriyah Contemporary Art Biennial, officially opened to the public on December 11 at the JAX Art District in Diriyah, northwest of Riyadh, the Saudi capital. A total of 64 artists from Saudi Arabia, China, and other countries are participating in the exhibition.
This biennial is jointly curated by the Saudi Diriyah Biennial Foundation and the UCCA Center for Contemporary Art in China, with Philip Tinari, director of the UCCA Center for Contemporary Art in China, serving as artistic director.
According to the curatorial team, the theme of this biennial is "Crossing the River by Feeling the Stones," which metaphorically refers to the reform strategies adopted during the period of socio-economic transformation and also reflects the current situation of Saudi Arabia's social and cultural development.
This biennial covers nearly 12,000 square meters, with exhibition halls spanning six interconnected buildings and presented in six sections: "Crossing the River by Feeling the Stones", "Inheritance as an Experiment", "Marginal Thinking", "Towards the Public", "Brave New World", and "On the Spirituality of Art".
Among them, the works of 27 Saudi artists account for more than 40% of the total number of exhibits, encompassing various forms such as painting, installation art and performance art; the works of 12 Chinese artists have also attracted much attention. Some artists use recycled materials in innovative ways to create works. For example, Xu Bing reconstructed a classic landscape painting with waste materials in "The Story Behind the Scenes Series: Endless Landscape" (2014).
Barkley, CEO of the Diriyah Biennale Foundation, said he hopes this year's biennale will establish an international dialogue, giving global audiences the opportunity to learn about Saudi Arabia's thriving cultural industry and creative communities, and strengthening interaction and exchange.
Philip Tinari said, "The biennial has a dual goal: to allow Saudi contemporary art to participate in global dialogue, and to allow Saudi audiences to immerse themselves in the world of contemporary art."
It is understood that a series of lectures will also be held during the opening week of the biennial, where artists, curators and opinion leaders from the creative industry will discuss topics such as cross-cultural exchange and the development of contemporary art.
