No need to say anything more, that's just how loyal Hua Hua is.
In the past two years, the US blockade and containment of Huawei's chips has not only plunged Huawei into an unprecedented predicament, but also caused huge losses to "US-affiliated" companies.
The US's suppression of China's chip industry, demanding that its own companies and related companies in allied countries simultaneously block my country's chip industry, has directly resulted in the impact on global chip suppliers' orders and profits, leading to reduced R&D investment and decreased production capacity for chip manufacturers, thereby causing shortages and disruptions in the global chip supply chain.
The chip shortage has now affected major industries around the world, such as car manufacturers halting production and mobile phone prices rising. Almost all industries that use chips are suffering from it.
In order to gain self-sufficiency in "chips," more and more technology giants in various countries are beginning to move towards "de-Americanization."
In order to firmly control the global semiconductor industry and contain the development of China's semiconductor industry, the United States has recently made a series of moves, such as hosting the "Chip Summit" and inviting giants from 64 countries to form a semiconductor alliance, and allocating funds to support American technology giants. For example, Intel, a long-established American technology giant, has invested $20 billion to build two wafer fabrication plants in Arizona, USA, and opened its chip foundry business to foreign companies in order to regain its dominant position in the chip field.
Most people thought that Intel's move would have a certain impact on TSMC and could very well take away TSMC's business.
The reason for this certainty is that Intel, as a long-established American technology giant, has been deeply involved in the semiconductor field for decades and possesses a large talent pool and technological reserves. It is bound to rise rapidly in the short term and defeat TSMC.
However, Morris Chang, the founder of TSMC, dismissed Intel's decision.
At the “2021 Master Think Tank Forum” held in April this year, Morris Chang made a surprising statement. Regarding Intel’s move to invest in building a wafer fab, Chang bluntly said: “It is quite ironic that Intel is building a chip foundry.”
Morris Chang's disdain for Intel's foray into the wafer foundry industry stems from his lingering resentment over a grudge between TSMC and Intel that began over 30 years ago.
In the 1960s and 70s, Intel was the jewel of American manufacturing, holding a dominant position in the global semiconductor industry.
Until the 1980s, the world's high-end semiconductor chips were controlled by a few powerful players.
At that time, the semiconductor industry was characterized by the IDM model, where chip design, manufacturing and packaging were all done by a single factory, and Intel was the representative of that era.
However, this model has become too much of a burden for some small businesses, and many semiconductor entrepreneurs can only look on in despair when faced with the huge costs of building production lines.
Driven by market demand, the chip industry began to see specialization and cooperation in the 1980s. In 1984, Morris Chang heard that there were companies that specialized in chip design, and he thought that since there were companies that specialized in design, then a factory that specialized in wafer manufacturing could be established.
Soon after, Morris Chang's vision became a reality, and TSMC was born.
TSMC focuses its main business on the single link of "wafer processing," without engaging in design, and only provides foundry services for wafer manufacturing.
At the time, TSMC, which had just been established, was just a small fry compared to the behemoth that was Intel.
In order to obtain capital support, Morris Chang once approached Intel for investment. However, when Intel heard that TSMC only handled the manufacturing process of the chip industry, it was clear that Intel was somewhat arrogant and looked down on TSMC, so it decisively refused to invest in TSMC.
Morris Chang also believed that Intel looked down on wafer fabrication services at the time.
It's surprising that the giant that looked down on wafer manufacturing services back then is now starting to do wafer foundry work.
Therefore, Morris Chang found it ironic that Intel had entered the wafer foundry business.
TSMC's market capitalization has now surpassed that of Intel.
Faced with TSMC's aggressive offensive, Intel naturally dared not remain complacent.
Today, TSMC is rushing towards 3nm chips, while Intel is still stuck at 14nm, which it was 7 years ago.
Catching up is not an easy task.
