A Date with the Stars | The Geminid Meteor Shower Will Reach Its Peak on the 14th - Xinhua News Agency
Tianjin, December 12 (Xinhua) -- Astronomical science experts say that the Geminid meteor shower, one of the three major meteor showers in the Northern Hemisphere and the last large-scale meteor shower of the year, will reach its peak on December 14. Meteor shower enthusiasts can observe it in the latter half of the night on that day.
The Geminid meteor shower was photographed by Beijing astronomy enthusiast An Jiu in Qinghai on December 13, 2018.
Most meteor showers are parent planets of periodic comets, but the Geminid meteor shower is parent planet 3200 Phaethon, an Apollo-type asteroid.
The Geminid meteor shower is also the second known meteor shower not "born" of a comet.
Xiu Lipeng, a director of the Tianjin Astronomical Society and an expert in popularizing astronomy, explained that just like a blockbuster movie, the Geminid meteor shower usually appears at the end of the year, and its "showcase period" can last from December 4th to 17th.
This meteor shower is known for its high and consistent meteor rate, and together with the Quadrantid meteor shower and the Perseid meteor shower, it is considered one of the three major meteor showers in the Northern Hemisphere.
A notable feature of the Geminid meteor shower is that the meteors are relatively slow-moving, have a rich variety of colors, and include many fireballs, making it suitable for both visual observation and photography for beginners in astrophotography.
The Geminid meteor shower was photographed by Yang Jing, an amateur astronomer from Tianjin, in Jizhou, Tianjin on December 13, 2020.
Astronomical forecasts indicate that this year's Geminid meteor shower will reach its peak around 3 PM on December 14th, with a ZHR (the number of meteors visible per hour when the radiant point is directly overhead under ideal viewing conditions) of 150.
Geminid meteor shower recommendation index chart.
Last year, the Geminid meteor shower left a deep impression on people with its spectacular display of meteors, but this year's Geminid meteor shower will be affected by moonlight, which will slightly diminish its brilliance.
The 14th is the 11th day of the 11th lunar month, and the moon will be a waxing gibbous moon. The bright moonlight will interfere with observation. Fortunately, the moon will set in the latter half of the night, and the radiant point of the Geminid meteor shower will also rise relatively high at this time.
Those who enjoy meteor showers can observe them in the hours following moonrise in the latter half of the night, but should take precautions against the cold.
How can we observe as many meteors as possible?
"It is not recommended to observe in the city. You can choose a place with a high altitude, low light pollution, and a wide view facing northeast in the suburbs or countryside, and then patiently wait for the moon to set before observing it visually."
It is important to note that the Geminid meteor shower has a large flow rate in all directions, so you don't need to keep staring at the radiant point of the Geminid meteor shower when observing it.
For photography enthusiasts who want to capture stunning "meteor shower" photos, it's best to choose a wide-angle lens with a large aperture and use a high ISO and the maximum aperture when shooting.
For stability and durability, a tripod, spare batteries, and a shutter release cable are also essential.
Xiu Lipeng reminded him.
What are the differences in market positioning between laser TVs and traditional TVs?
As I understand it, the traditional TV the questioner is referring to is probably an LCD TV. The main differences between laser TVs and LCD TVs in terms of market positioning are as follows:
First, laser TVs are more focused on the large-screen market.
Compared to the widespread market positioning of LCD TVs, laser TVs are clearly more focused on the large-screen market, or rather, laser TVs are products designed for large screens.
Currently, the mainstream LCD TV sizes are mostly between 55 and 65 inches, while laser TVs are generally 75 inches or larger, with the largest exceeding 100 inches, fully meeting users' demand for large-screen TVs.
In recent years, the global shipments and sales share of laser TVs have been increasing, accounting for more than 60% of the total sales of TVs 80 inches and above.
According to CMM's forecast, the laser TV market will see sales growth of over 140% in 2020, continuing its rapid growth.
The reason why laser TVs have achieved such good results in the large-screen market is mainly due to their excellent performance in eye protection.
Based on the imaging principle of diffuse reflection in laser TVs, the light emitted by the laser source does not shine directly into the eyeball. Compared with the backlight of LCD TVs, the imaging process is closer to the imaging process of objects under natural conditions, and it is less irritating to the eyes.
The CESI Laboratory of the China Electronics Technology Standardization Institute and ophthalmologists from Peking Union Medical College Hospital conducted a rigorous comparative test on laser TVs and LCD TVs under the same conditions, obtaining 144 sets of test data.
Data confirms that laser TVs do indeed have strong eye-protection properties, and even have a certain improvement effect in specific aspects.
With vision health receiving increasing attention, laser TVs have not only attracted more and more users with their eye-protection advantages, but have also opened up another breakthrough in the color TV market.
Second, laser TVs are more focused on the high-end market.
In contrast to the continuous decline in LCD TV prices, most laser TVs currently on the market are priced above 10,000 yuan, and their prices are gradually increasing as their size and light source are upgraded.
Why are laser TVs so expensive?
There must be a reason for that.
With the continuous development of light sources and technology, laser TVs have many advantages that LCD TVs and projectors cannot achieve.
Thanks to ultra-short throw projection technology, laser TVs have a shorter projection distance compared to traditional projection devices, enabling a 100-inch large-screen experience at a short distance. They require little space, and the main unit is compact, taking up very little room.
In terms of brightness, major brand laser TVs can reach over 2000 lumens.
In addition, it generates less heat, causes less wear and tear on the equipment, and has a longer lifespan for the television.
In addition, many high-end laser TV models are equipped with true 4K ultra-high-definition picture quality, artificial intelligence systems, bionic screens and many other cutting-edge technologies, which can bring users a more stunning audio-visual experience.
It's not a pseudo-demand, but rather a product of demand segmentation. In terms of picture quality and return on investment, laser TVs are not for audio-visual enthusiasts. If you want to balance the large screen and the lack of a suitable viewing environment, you can give it a try. Everything has its advantages and disadvantages, so you can weigh them and make your own judgment. The worst thing is to believe only one side of the story.
Simply put, ultra-wide-angle near-focus projectors—laser TVs—have to use expensive ultra-wide-angle lenses and reflectors in order to get close to the screen, which does not conform to optimal optical design.
To block some ambient light, a microstructured Fresnel screen is used, which is very expensive; the price of an 80-inch screen is basically the same as that of a 65-inch LCD screen.
Another point is that I particularly hate projector manufacturers using the idea that diffuse reflection is good for the eyes as a selling point. Please, the light on the screen that the eyes can see is direct light to the eyes. If you diffuse it onto the ceiling, the eyes can't see it. If you insist on being pedantic, LCD TVs also diffuse "direct light," but when you turn on the TV, doesn't the ceiling also get lit up?
Moreover, if the projection screen does not reflect light diffusely, it cannot form an image at all.
The hot spot (light spot) effect of high-gain screens is often overlooked. When a large amount of light is reflected into the eyes from a certain angle, it is truly uncomfortable.
