Is it reliable to buy insurance for small umbrellas?
Xiaoyusan is an online insurance brokerage platform.
In terms of the establishment conditions: According to the "Regulations on the Supervision of Insurance Brokerage Institutions (2015 Revision)," to become an insurance brokerage company, three key requirements must be met: shareholders and founders must have no major illegal records in the past three years, the minimum capital requirement is RMB 50 million, and approval from the China Insurance Regulatory Commission is required.
These three conditions are actually quite stringent. In summary, it requires the company to have the strength, to be approved by the China Banking and Insurance Regulatory Commission (a national authority that regulates insurance companies and banks nationwide), and for its shareholders to have a good work ethic. As an insurance brokerage company, Xiaoyusan Insurance doesn't need to question whether it is legitimate or not, since these three thresholds are not something that every insurance company can meet.
In this respect, it's not bad; it's trustworthy.
From the perspective of insurance products: Xiaoyusan Insurance is like an insurance supermarket. Many companies' star critical illness insurance products are sold on this platform, such as the newly launched HeTai Super Mary No. 5 Critical Illness Insurance. The claims payer and the insurer are both HeTai Life Insurance. Xiaoyusan Insurance is just a third-party intermediary, so there is no need to question its reliability.
In terms of payment methods: Internet platform products generally offer better value for money because they eliminate the operating costs of physical branches and the cost of sales staff. Moreover, they offer flexible payment options, supporting monthly payments, which reduces the financial burden on policyholders and maximizes the leverage of insurance.
That's quite good.
That's something to consider.
From the perspective of the salesperson's professionalism: This is particularly important because insurance is an industry that requires a high degree of professionalism. Many internet product customers can purchase insurance on their own, which can lead to many misunderstandings. In terms of health disclosure and occupation, non-insurance professionals often add their own subjective opinions when applying for insurance, thinking that they are healthy or meet the requirements. This can easily lead to many potential claims problems and the risk of being denied a claim.
I myself have worked in insurance telemarketing for "Tencent WeSure" (which, like Xiaoyusan, is an internet insurance brokerage platform), and I can tell you this with full responsibility.
Online insurance is genuine and reliable; the unreliable aspect is the people involved. Online channels lack professional staff and are prone to misleading sales practices.
For example, the marketing strategies of "1 yuan insurance for 6 million yuan coverage", "buy insurance and get a free mobile phone", and "free critical illness coverage of 60,000 yuan" are not wrong, but they avoid the important issues and do not tell the policyholders that the first month is 1 yuan, and the following month will be charged at the normal rate, ranging from tens to 200 yuan. Many customers are charged for one or two years without knowing what they have bought.
They thought they could spend 1 yuan and the insurance company would pay them 6 million (like a windfall).
The free mobile phone is only given away with insurance policies ending in special numbers like 6666 or 8888. And if you don't redeem the prize after receiving the winning text message, no one will remind you.
(This is another trap for policyholders) The free 60,000 yuan critical illness coverage is only short-term. If you rely solely on this and don't have other commercial insurance, what can 60,000 yuan do if you actually suffer a critical illness? It won't solve the problem, and your life will be completely unprotected from now on.
The government is currently cracking down on misleading practices in online insurance sales.
So, all things considered, the platform is fine, the product is fine, the problem lies with the sales staff's professionalism and ethics.
I suggest you consider this carefully. In fact, many offline insurance brokerage companies offer a wider range of products, giving customers more choices and options. Some of their products are even more cost-effective than online products.
I have personally helped 59 online clients by underwriting offline products, saving each person 2,000-3,000 yuan per year in premiums.
If you have any questions, please feel free to contact me.
Me: Mingya Insurance Broker, with 3 years of experience in corporate management training, having served nearly a thousand corporate clients and partnered with over 100 insurance companies. Before a client applies for insurance, I will start from their needs and tailor-make insurance products for them. During the application process, I will compare prices from multiple companies for the client and do my best to obtain the best underwriting results. After the application is submitted, I will organize the policy and manage the policy for the client, so that the client can have peace of mind.
We grow together with every client for life.
I hope my answer can be helpful to the questioner!
According to the definition of insurance regulators, internet insurance is an insurance business in which policyholders can independently complete all the insurance application processes after clicking on an application link.
During this process, neither the policyholder nor the insurance advisor needs to sign; all steps can be completed independently by the policyholder.
Although online insurance purchases lack a sense of "ceremony" and may not even have a printed paper contract, this does not affect the validity and legal effect of the electronic contract.
This model is somewhat similar to a "telemarketing" assembly line operation, but there is a fatal problem with buying insurance in this way, namely, that after-sales service may not be able to keep up.
Insurance is usually a long-term contract that lasts for decades. When purchasing insurance, shouldn't we carefully consider whether the "intermediary" we choose is an "insurance intermediary" that can accompany us for a long time and continue to provide services to us many years later?
